A first virtual operator will win Czechia this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in Czech Republic is relatively advanced, our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force classic operators to lower prices.
Maybe he won't be missing for long.
We have already mentioned, on many occasions, the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The ČTÚ (The Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of a SMS was higher in us than in the rest of the Union, confirmed it.
As a result of the latest steps taken by the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming fees, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be for some customers of Czech mobile operators less expensive than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in Czech Republic are maintained so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really want to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that is well above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this regard, Pavel Dvořák, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), who has stated on several occasions that there was no room for another operator in Czech Czech telecommunications office (ČTÚ) in Czech Czech Republic, which has been coerced with the operators.
It is likely that a classic operator with its own network has no longer seemed to have much chance (in fact, now it would find only hardly frequencies).
But there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that led to a substantial fall in prices, to which conventional operators were also to react.
However, even before the entry of the parties such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the market, voices similar to those heard today at home were heard in Britain.
However, it appeared that there was still room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We are not obliged to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch of the Virtual Mobilking operator in Poland.
In just six months, this operator managed to earn more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
Let's add that behind Mobilking, there's the Penta financial group, which has, among other things, the U:phone in Czech.
The advantage of virtual operators is that it is possible to focus on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be effective, they actually need much less customers than a conventional operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the relatively high costs of construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
This is why in the world, virtual operators profile themselves as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited offer of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers text messages in Britain at least twice as expensive as its competitors.
However, as shown by the example of Mobilking in Poland, placing on an unusual target group can also be a good shot of advertising.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
"The real men choose Mobilking - an operator they like and whom they can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would also be able to walk at home.
Miroslav Čepický, the spokesman for Vodafone, doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the supply of services."
In Czech Republic, no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the successful expansion of this project, but in Czech negotiations are not very encouraging.
The launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries in our area," said in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group.
It thus indirectly confirmed that operators in Czech Republic were not, in any case, in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to make every effort to prevent a potential competitor from appearing.
The GTS Novera group, who would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telephonika in the business customer field, has not been hiding, for long enough, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We have a lot to be able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have already conducted negotiations on this possibility on several occasions with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have succeeded in the negotiations," said the spokesperson of the Pavel Kaidl group.
So the future may be promising.
According to unofficial information, it seems that we might be able to welcome the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for the moment, his creation is accompanied by total silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is in comparison with other very specific markets.
At the moment, no subject with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," said Vlastimil Sršeň of the Press Department of Telephonika O2, in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also relate to the specificity of the Czech market.
The spokesperson for T-Mobile Martina Kemrová stated in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not yet registered a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a basis."
And she adds: "It is practically excluded that a virtual operator appears in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited time, we should now have a concrete agreement."
Vodafone instead directs its attention to the completion of requests to obtain its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický says in relation to this: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
That is what we think means the most from a client's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to establish a common network for a fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities: in phase with operators
The mobile operators' approach is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and thus a decrease in their profits.
So what good is it to facilitate the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, operators know how to feel like larvae in the fair. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:phone also testifies to it.
The greatest apparent pressure on the ČTÚ, when creating the U:fon, was that exercised by the T-Mobile company.
This demonstrates information available to the public from the ČTÚ web pages.
Today, however, the U:fon is willing to serve as an argument not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted in this regard: "Competition on the mobile market has also been recently enhanced by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the character of the RT mobile market, it is clear that the entry of an additional player would, and above all its services, subject it to high requirements."
But given the attitude of the mobile operators here, the indifference of the Czech regulators seems disconcerting.
However, it is not just the attitude of ČTÚ, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, has unfortunately not the power to intervene in the economic competition in Czech Republic.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
However, the latter adopts, in the face of this problem, its typical position.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the relevant virtual operator concerning the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been concluded at the moment, because the offer of potential stakeholders has not previously presented sufficient interest for conventional operators," he said in response to our question Kristián Chalupa of the UOHS Department of External Relations.
A statement made in this way would not surprise representatives of the operators.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, also take care, that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, such a declaration is more than misleading.
Even more so as Kristián Chalupa adds: "In other countries, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile phone services."
However, pressure towards an honest functioning of the market and lower prices is apparently not part of UOHS' interests.
What is actually shocking is the almost touching agreement of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, if it really is a coincidence, naturally arises.
In the same way, a price of gasoline strictly identical to all service stations is probably due to chance and tough competition.
"The Office has not identified signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this respect, so it has no reason to intervene in one way or another.
None of the operators have a dominant position, none therefore have an increased corresponding responsibility for their behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably even lacking the telecommunications regulator," said Chaloupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the ČTÚ that telecommunications constitutes, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators have a dominant position on such a market.
However, some law experts propose another view of things: for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, the consent of the network operator must be obtained at each time.
And the mobile operator quite logically has the monopoly on its network.
This is how it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the UOHS that three mobile operators proceed visibly in a similar manner.
However, complaints from many interested parties (including GTS Novera, mentioned above) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Taking responsibility for the ČTÚ is a fairly common turn in communications, through which UOHS washes its hands.
We have already met this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to introduce the recently adopted Telecommunications Act in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised to improve the situation.
This, the representatives of the UOHS must know very well, but their interests seem to be somewhere else.
When no one looks, it can work
However, the operation of some kind of virtual pseudo-operators, many in Czech mobile networks, remains unseen.
These are companies publishing their own price lists of mobile telephone services, but they are only partly public.
In most cases, companies dealing with multi-level marketing are involved.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer specialized mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies generally reach only elected ones.
The magic tower consists of the fact that the company faces the operator is a classic company customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she gets special (and other) price offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If what you're referring to happened, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions that we're going to consider and that could lead to an end to collaboration with the society in question," answered our question about this Martina Kemrová problem.
However, it is unlikely that an echo of such an activity will not reach the managers of mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned it can be thousands of customers.
No operator, however, is against such a procedure.
In fact, the activities of these companies bring them non-negligible benefits, and at the same time, as opposed to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out the possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are used only by a percentage of negligible customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card on their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the manner of ordinary customers of mobile operators."
But that is precisely what should seem strange to the ČTÚ.
In addition, another question is asked at UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes on such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the UOHS has relatively broad powers to reveal such an activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions forbid it.
When we are no longer the most expensive country
As we have mentioned on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a substantial decrease in the price of services.
However, practically in all countries where virtual operators appeared, traditional operators were trying, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small or even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it was precisely at this level that the regulatory bodies in developed countries, which defended not the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers, were involved.
Both by formal measures and by informal pressure, they eventually obtained the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators deal with this issue in the way of a hot potato that is disposed of by transmitting it to a nearby target.
As a result of the experiences we have, we can only get rid of the impression that confusion in skills is more than profitable in these cases.
But let's not throw the handle after the cog.
If the flow information says true and a virtual operator will soon appear in our home, the Czech mobile market may be in motion.
If one of the operators accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the UOHS could hardly remain impassible in the face of rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And perhaps we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on Czech National Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov mönj (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem was again recorded by the national theatre orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo song, a choir interpretation and an instrumental version.
The song is provided by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiaš and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the anthem's arrangements.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek considers Czech national singing as one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted to Český rozhlas (Czech public radio), he chose for the interpretation of solo versions of singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I was trying to take care that the two singers, as well as the choir, have a good dictionary, so that we understand the words well, that they sing simultaneously," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate next year's 175th anniversary.
For the first time in 1834, Kde domov played on the boards of Stavovské divadlo (the State Theatre) in Fidlovačka (Kermesse des savetiers), a Czech original piece by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by the music of František Škroup.
It became popular and people spontaneously appropriated it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first couplet naturally became an integral part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
