The South Africans called for a referendum in the USA
In 1945, the South Germans called for Šumava to be integrated into the United States.
This stems from a letter filed in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (The Southern Bohemian Scientific Library).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want at least to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of South Germans allegedly addressed the President of the USA with such a desire.
This stems from a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
Germans from Český Krumlov ask in the letter the American president not to allow "šumavská župa" (forest region south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation and want to be truly sure that the words proclaiming that the American troops come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," is written in the letter, signed "People, whom the fate of Šumava is at heart."
Since the accession to Czechoslovakia is allegedly promising - by knowing the Czech national character - only of brutality, attitude without regard, misunderstanding, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take the protection of Šumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe, that you would grant this territory to a foreign state to us, which oppresses and destroys minorities and has not contributed to the Allies' victory without considering the opinion of the quarter of millions of people," is written in the letter.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of the "Czech oppressors".
If the president of the USA questioned the opinion of the Germans of Šumava, he would only have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to determine whether his inhabitants wanted to be part of the USA, or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, in view of the current knowledge of post-war history, seem somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it well illustrates the expectations of the Germans of the Southeasts of the time.
While the Czech Germans had to at least think that the question of their expulsion from the Republic would arise, very few of them admitted such an opportunity.
Some hoped that the United States and Great Britain would obtain some kind of autonomy for the South.
Others thought they'd just stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirmed this.
During the war, it was, as German of Česke Budějovice, engaged in the Navy in the Baltic countries.
When he was captured by the English at the end of the war and placed in the catch camp of the Holstein region, dozens of Czech Germans came to see him to teach them the Czech.
"They believed that once they returned home, the Czech would benefit them," said Chalupa.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war believed that, following the Beneš Decrees, he would be expelled from the republic.
