"I photograph the master out of the scene to capture elements of his character" Günther Bauer - Photographer
No heels, no foreign clothes.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, freed from all tensions to obtain the relaxed aspect of man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, the person.
Inseparable except in the privacy, in these unknown moments of the general public, where we discover with intimate gestures and stolen eyes of artists who do not care to ride on stage.
German Günther Bauer mixes in "Flamenco - people" the theatricality of some plays with singers, dancers and guitarists with this less known side of artists.
In this project, the photographer resumes the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the programming of the Flemish Photography Month, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, greater every day," explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "may be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that these are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "in the street" are artists capable of transmitting on the scene of passion, sadness, joy ... by captivating the public.
To capture moments of personality of these artists you don't need to take pictures on stage.
They have a clean personality and character.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere that allows me to capture with the camera the moments of personality of the flamenco stars."
With the festival "Cant populaire des Mines", Bauer began a long journey in 1997 to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a flat camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of the camera and the equipment, recall classical photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classic side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day".
It is not about dancing or singing in itself, but about the personality and character of the artist who captures the audience with his art.
The search for the essentials and magic has been the constant of this work presented these days at the gallery El Fotómata.
The flamenco stars such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy photographers.
The project has become an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a collection book of portraits exposed to the gallery.
The passion for Bauer's portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of Old Sports" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves to photograph the portrait of people, to know them and to be able to enter their lives for a moment more or less.
I think in photography the portrait is the most difficult kind.
You find yourself in front of people, characters that sometimes you don't know or that just give you a few minutes to get a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true."
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco called "Flamenco - people", is exhibited at the Galerie El Fotómata, located at the 20th Street of Mata (tree parallel to the Peopleaie d'Hercule) which will be opened until 16 October next.
