"Mayo's Blood," Garci's ossuary
Drawing from the stories of Benito Pérez Galdós, José Luis Garci recreates the famous battle of the Spaniards against the French in "May Blood", which is the most ambitious film of his filmography with nearly 15 million euros of budget.
The filmmaker tried "to stage the many characters and illustrate the social analysis" that he always admired in the work of the famous novelist, he explained today during the presentation of the film, with Quim Gutiérrez and Paula Echevarría at the head of the long list of actors.
The film lasting more than two and a half hours, "May Blood" will be released in the cinemas next Friday, which will then become a television series for Telemadrid for more than four hours.
Grand admirer of Galdós literature, José Luis Garci makes sure that he realized with this film "a child's dream" thanks to Esperanza Aguirre, who commissioned him three years ago to turn a memorial film for the two hundred years of May 2, Madrid, which he always accepted when the story was held to national historical facts.
The 15 million euros provided by the City of Madrid constitute a "one opportunity" for Garci to reproduce with the appropriate decorations and clothing the atmosphere of "a Spain that has deceived itself as leader for the fight, since the struggle for independence has led the people to rebellions under the reign of Ferdinand VII", he said.
But the filmmaker regrets that he did not get funding as for the films "Captain Alatriste" or "The Ghosts of Goya" - more than double that obtained for "May Blood",- because he was unable to turn some scenes written in a script signed by Horacio Valcárcel, with whom he collaborated during almost his entire career.
The filmmaker of "Rear has started" influenced his usual way of working, on the stage of actors, with whom he usually repeats before starting the shooting and to whom he does not cast, since it seems "humble" to him and considers that "the role of the filmmaker is to go to the theatre and to the cinema to keep himself informed".
Many actors in "Blood of May" repeat in front of the camera, such as Miguel Rellán, Carlos Larragañaga or Fernando Guilllen Cuervo.
Four times the Oscar candidate (he won one), Garci considers that the three candidate films that represent Spain this year at the Academy of Hollywood, "May Blood", "Seven tables of French billiard" and finally the winner, "The blind sunflowers", are not representative of the young Spanish cinema, "which would deserve to be better known," he said.
With this film Garci doesn't expect a price.
"In the beginning you think you're working for posterity, and then you realize that you're working for prosperity, and now you're happy to make an extra movie," says Garci after more than 30 years of career.
Isabelle Bayón puts herself in the skin of the Sevilla dancer Tortola Valencia
A Sevillan dancer will pay tribute to an equally Sevillan dancer.
Carmen Tortola Valencia, daughter of a Catalan father (Florenç Tortola Ferrer) and a Andalusian mother (Georina Valencia Valenzuela), was born in the district of Triana and who at the age of three will live in London with her family.
She was a free dance dancer and a specialist in Eastern dances.
She had an exciting life, a pioneer in the liberation of the woman, such as Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was Buddhist and vegetarian and pleaded for the abolition of corset that prevented the free movement of women.
The life of this woman, who marked the history of dance in Europe between the two wars, fascinated Isabelle Bayón.
"I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and the latter offered me to interpret the Sevilla dancer Tortola Valencia and it seemed incredible to me."
According to the dancer, "we're not trying to tell her life but to translate her way of thinking.
His dance titles made me think of flamenco.
Thus, "the butterfly dance" made me think of a Cuban popular dance and "the snake dance" to some tangos.
His dance was sensual and they told me that my way of dancing was the same as his," she said.
The stage was made thanks to two remarkable contributions: that of Miguel Poveda who will sing again Isabela in one of his shows, as he had done at "The Open Door"; and that of Professor Matilde Coral, who exceptionally wanted to collaborate with the one who was his student.
"Matilde turns Tortola into a mature character.
I am happy that she has agreed to play a role in my work and it honors me."
The stage was also made thanks to the musical composition and guitars of Jesús Torres y Paco Arriaga, the popular song of Michel Ortega, el Pulga y Moi de Morón; the percussions of El Pájaro, as well as the rape of Rafa El Viola and the collaboration of an actor, Juanfra Juárez, "who plays the role of the eternal companion of these kinds of artists who were considered divas".
This work also tells, in a way, the life of this woman who has exhibited herself in places so far away, especially for the time being, such as India, the United States, or Russia, but also throughout Europe, since she usually lived in London.
"I wanted to remind her because I think it's these women who have a huge influence in their time and now nobody knows and doesn't value her work," Bayón says.
