Alcohol repeaters on the wheel will have to install the 'alcock' system
The Minister of the Interior wants the driver who has had more than three administrative alcohol sanctions, to install in his vehicle a system that prevents the vehicle from starting drunk, or if he does not suffer.
The initiative was already announced last June and now appears in the report of the Minister of State in which this initiative is considered a pilot project that will last one year.
Its purpose is to reintegrate the driver by offering him road rehabilitation courses.
The Minister of State for Road Safety but also the Directorate-General for Road Safety and the Technology Institute for Automobile Safety Foundation will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists arrested for driving more than once in a drunken state resume the car.
Alcohol would avoid this because it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the alcohol rate in the haloine and prevents starting the vehicle if the driver does not blow before; or when the driver's alcohol rate is higher than the permitted one.
Its cost is more than 1,000 euros and is borne by the driver.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device reduced up to 65% of the offences during the first year of installation.
And in Spain it is estimated that this could save 115 people every year.
This applies only to administrative sanctions for two reasons: dealing with such behaviours before they turn into criminal offences.
And facilitate its implementation, since legal reform can be done by ordinary means, but criminal reform requires reform of the organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although some industrial and functional vehicles already have an experimental vehicle.
The Congress of Deputies will vote tomorrow for an initiative by the Spanish Socialist Party which proposes to install this system on school buses as has been done in France.
