Interview - Blood Safe Again
Héma-Québec celebrated yesterday the 10th anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. Francine Decary, was right to rejoice because Héma-Québec became one of the world's most secure and effective blood providers.
And above all, he regained the public's confidence that had been seriously shaken by the blood scandal contaminated in the 1980s and 1990s.
As it is known, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In February 1994 the Government of Canada initiated a public inquiry, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances leading to such a tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster would not be repeated.
While Judge Krever was late to file his report, some provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec started his activities, only 38% of people still trusted in the blood system in Quebec, Dr. Decary recalled.
The situation was discouraging.
As a result of efforts to improve the safety of blood products and labour on the ground during the years that followed, we have regained public confidence," she said before proudly affirming that at the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of Quebec's population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Decary points out that "trust is something extremely fragile."
Since its inception on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, many cases of the human form of the mad cow disease, a new variant of the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, have emerged in Europe.
"And we did not know at all whether this disease could be transmitted by blood.
It was then based on one of the main recommendations in the Krever and Gelineau reports that when it is unknown and that a serious disease can result from it, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain inevitably leading to death, exclusion measures are introduced.
In April 1999, the blood of people who had been living in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980 was refused.
But a few years ago, it was demonstrated beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode has shown us that the precautionary principle applied has meaning."
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique of HIV testing appeared on the market: nucleic acid (TAN) tests that allow donors to detect directly in their blood the presence of the virus itself and not the antibody against the virus, on which the tests used so far were based.
The TANs have made it possible to shorten the mute period, which extends between the time when the person was infected and where the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than a week.
This has substantially reduced the risk of some donors being infected without knowledge and cannot be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products annually, it will take more than 24 years before a case of transmission of HIV by a blood product occurs.
I believe that today one can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health," said the head of management of Hema-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than last year the Chikungunya virus, like the West Nile virus, appeared on Réunion Island, was transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant," continued Dr. Décary before pointing out that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for sufficient supply.
"Necessities increase because the population ages.
Since anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a refill of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences on the blood donor network, which is on average only 3% of Quebec's eligible for blood donation."
Any person in health who is 18 years of age and over meets the eligibility criteria may, however, donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 per cent of those who offer their blood are not accepted because they are infected with AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria is severe, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortcomings are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this network of donors as they grow old and can no longer give their blood.
However, it is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but above all to hold them back and encourage them to become regular donors.
Today's life is so frightful, we rarely find the time to spend an hour giving of his blood," says Francine Decary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec provides not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eye cells and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These fabrics are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public bank of cord blood in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was previously considered a biomedical waste is full of blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat severe diseases, such as leukaemia.
"We celebrated a few weeks ago the banking of our thousandth sample of cord blood and we plan to collect more than a thousand each year.
We should start proposing them for grafts at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Decary, who describes this cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that there is no access," because Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
