Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and the heads of the Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the US$700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has rocked Wall Street for months must still be endorsed by both Congress Chambers.
In particular, it provides: better control by the electors of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for default of payment, as well as a right to look at wages paid to the leaders of the assisted companies.
American Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, President of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective on the markets," said the representative of the Bush administration, Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done to protect the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street," the democrat explained.
"This is the fundamental point: if we don't do this, the trauma, chaos and disturbances on the daily lives of Americans will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had been sprinted in the last few hours in fear of the effect of a further failure on investors' mood.
The deadline for opening up the markets was this morning.
The two candidates for the U.S. presidential election, who were later associated with negotiations, were rather favourable to the agreement, although they did not fail to express their discontent that they were forced to reach this end.
Senator Democrat Barack Obama has given himself the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, including that of allowing the owners to retain their homes and the salary of state-recovery business leaders.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is no welcome.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on the American television waves.
Asked about another channel to see if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, said, "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The big lines I've read show that it's something we're all going to have to digest and with which we're going to be able to move forward.
The option of not doing anything is simply not acceptable," he said.
The 700 billion plan aims to redeem with taxpayers' money the suspicious, risk-active and unsold claims of U.S. financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the breakdown of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of risk mortgage credits (subpressed) before expanding to other more widespread forms of credit securities (CCAs) and leading to liquidity freezes and bank and financial institution deficits.
It was a group of elected Republicans who had brought forward the first draft agreement last week.
It is believed to have come out of this deadlock since Democrats have agreed that some "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to round the angles for everyone in Congress, a provision has also been added stipulating that if the government were to incur losses for five years with this program, it could put in place new taxes to help it recover its implementation.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first tranche of 250 billion to be added to another 100 billion if the President deems it necessary.
The payment of 350 billion more should be endorsed by another vote of the Congress.
In exchange for its aid, Washington will obtain shares in the assisted companies that will be worth dividends in the event of profit and that it will be able to resell when the storm is over.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay the seizure procedures for housing related to the real estate loans concerned by this plan, as well as to set limits on compensation and severance allowances paid to the leaders of the affected companies.
The architects of the plan would like to see him put to the vote in the House of Representatives today, and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green fire.
In fact, votes continued to rise against this project yesterday, both in the Republican and Democrat camp.
"Of course, Washington does not hear you," said Republican Scott Garrett, member of the House's Finance Committee, to his constituents.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that consists of taking advantage of taxpayers."
Animator of a small group at Congress called "the caucus of skeptics", Democratic representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred eminent economic professors, including three Nobel Prizes, wrote to tell us: Congress is asked not to hurry and carefully examine the way to go," he said yesterday.
At the same time, there was once again evidence of the global nature of the crisis in Europe.
