The psychology of the auction: why do we spend more money?
During auction sales, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the goods.
Researchers in neurology and economics at the University of New York have succeeded in updating the neurological and economic bases of this apparently irrational known behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be separated during this type of competition, such as a sale on eBay auctions, which is why they prefer even to pay too high a price.
These researches tried to draw up a neurological pattern of this kind of "game" using experimental auction sales.
One of the volunteer groups played in the loto, while the other group took part in a play auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance (MRI) process, researchers analyzed the active brain domains of experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the sale to auctions, one essential element of which is the over auction of a third, the whole being under the brain stem, called striatum, was moved intensively during the loss of the party.
This part of the brain, alongside several other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-stimulation" of the nervous system.
This is why, according to researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the leak in the face of the violent response of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economists of this group of researchers continued financial monitoring analyses.
In these cases, three groups were over-involved against a partner in various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and they did so.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they were winning the game, then they would receive an additional $15 in reward.
While the third group received this $15 prior to the auction, the members of the group also lost that money, in case they lost the auctions.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the emphasis was placed on one on victory, while the other on failure.
By proving the hypothesis of neurologists, members of the team of players "against failure" were willing to put higher than those performed by the control group and the "for victory" group.
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
In fact, each of them explained the phenomena observed in auction sales only by the pleasure of winning and the parade before the risk.
Only the neurological imaging methods helped eliminate the contradiction between the two theories by leading, now, to a third explanation." - Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economic Sciences of the University of New York, observed.
Hepatitis: When should we consult a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while chronic liver disease is mentioned among the first causes of death in Hungary.
It is estimated that patients with hepatitis virus in Hungary are 100 miles away, but only seven miles are treated. This is due to the fact that patients often do not know they are carriers of the virus.
Hepatitis name is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and yellowness are characteristic, but pathogens and diseases generated differ from one another.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogens, are mainly spread in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tube (e.g. contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses by blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, vaccination against A and B viruses is recommended. There is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after the consumption of contaminated foods, generally accompanied by a poor general condition, weakness, stomach disease and nausea.
Then it develops on the skin and on the white eye a visible yellowness, the saddles become clearer and the urine takes a darker color. The healing can take two to three weeks.
Around the world, every year, one million people die in the most severe form of this pathology, such as liver cancer or cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause of this is that, according to estimates, only one in ten patients receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if it is not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most of the patients do not know how to reach the virus, because the pathogen destroys liver cells in a sneezing manner. In many cases, the first symptoms only appear after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular testing.
Contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who had a blood transfusion prior to 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with chronic hepatitis C in the world.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your doctor who treats symptoms of unknown origin as soon as symptoms are observed.
The disease can be cured if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, thus the risk of infection disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
30 September is the world day of hepatitis, first organized in 2004 by agencies representing patients from all over the world.
Its aim is to draw attention to the cirrhosis of the chronic liver caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does he who believes in God feel less pain?
According to recent research results, religious belief would function as some kind of analgesic, which would have already contributed to making the death of Catholic martyrdom more bearable.
The British daily Telegraph published an article that researchers at Oxford University have had an interesting experience in analyzing how belief in God could influence tolerance to the pain of the human being.
As part of this experience for the least odd, 12 Catholic believers and so many atheists were subjected to electroshocks, while each of them observed a painting representing the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude much of the suffering.
Thanks to a technique of palpation of the human brain, it was also discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for the regulation of pain.
This analysis is the first of a series of experiences, which are attended by academics, scholars, philosophers and theologians from different sectors of the university.
Specifically, the experience is carried out as follows: an instrument emitting sparks and disseminating electroshocks is fixed on the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked participants of the experience to look in a sustained way at two paintings, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady with the Hermine painted by Leonard de Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers at the origin of this experience hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary evoked a kind of state of faith among the believers, while the choice of the painting of Da Vinci, not very different from the first, concerned its soothing effect.
Experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during that time, they received 20 electroshocks in four succeeding parts, while looking either at the religious theme painting or the more general theme painting.
The Catholics stated that in the eyes of the Virgin Mary, they felt like "safe", as someone whose "care" is taken care of and they "calmed, and peace invaded them".
In view of the painting of religious theme, they reported 12% pain less than when they looked at Leonard's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experience, believes that we can achieve the same effects with any other strong image, in the atheists, provided we find the appropriate photo.
"We should find an image against which they react very positively, such as a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
Tom Wright, Anglican bishop, welcomed the results of these researches.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases change our personality," Wright added.
After these excellent results, there remains only the question of what would be the effect on the regulation of the pain of the subjects if one shows believers a Madonna painted by Léonard or by a painter of the same size?
Would the view of a better quality Virgin Mary lead to better results?
