The intelligent car imitates the flight of the bourdon
What method would be better for developing technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, if not the imitation of an existing obstacle detector in nature?
Like, for example, bees.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC, taking place in Japan, boudoning bees gave the strategic idea of starting engineers at Nissan, to inspire them on how they should design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built a mini robot, a bio-inspired auto-robotized control system, BR23C-type, which he equipped with bees' qualities, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
On its flight, each bee is its own, oval-shaped space, which actually resembles much of our secure protection hull - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the research and development department and technological public relations of the brand.
The facet eye of the bee plays a vital role, as it is able to see in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
In order to imitate the functions of the facet eye, the engineers discussed the idea of the laser telemeter.
It identifies the obstacles in an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the aboard microprocessor, which transforms it into avoidance maneuver immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it at an angle sufficient to avoid collision.
Contrary to any existing system, this avoidance manoeuvre is carried out in a whole instinctive way.
"If not, the mini robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and most internal layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for the time being the collision is considered inevitable.
This whole process must reflect what bees do to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in a close eye.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees have to avoid other bees, in our case, only the rotational movement, acceleration and slowdown could be used as manoeuvres at the disposal of the mini robot
The BR23C uses polymer lithium batteries that are lighter and the energy concentration is higher, making their life span longer than in the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the smart instinctive reaction that is paramount, not data processing, and even less capacity to store.
This mechanism should only treat some incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilo-bytes of continuous memory.
There is no need for memory of a giga-bytes capacity, not even mega-bytes.
This is the first step towards the design of a technology for instant avoidance. According to Nissan's estimates, this system will make its way into the cars manufactured in series in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on his way.
