Industrial prices have continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 - the Central Office of Statistics of Hungary reported.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, while compared to those of a previous year, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic prices and exports, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to those in the previous month, and by 3.2 per cent compared with those in the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices have only increased to a lesser extent: 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry have only experienced a slight increase in the order of 0.1 per cent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with first, the manufacture of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, then the production of footwear with 2.5 per cent monthly increase.
The higher prices of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a considerable monthly increase in the prices of the manufacturing sector of chemicals and products (1.6 per cent).
This resulted in deflation in the oil processing sectors (1.4 per cent), the manufacture of electrical machinery and apparatus (0.9 per cent), as well as a minimum increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
The other sectors of the processing industry have increased from 0.2 per cent to 0.9 per cent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which represent a significant weight in the national industrial operation, prices increased by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in the gas price established by the authorities since 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison, taking into account the domestic sales of the processing sectors, the prices of the oil processing sector have increased most significantly (32.4 per cent).
In the metal manufacturing sector, prices rose by 13.2 per cent, while prices rose by 11 per cent in the major area of food, beverages and tobacco production.
Price reductions were made in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of machinery and electrical appliances (0.3 per cent).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, the price increases ranged from 0.6 per cent to 9.1 per cent.
In the processing industry as a whole, prices increased by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
The prices of the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded 18.7 per cent of the previous year.
Among the internal trade groups and according to the allocation of sectors, in August, it was the investment profit-initiating sectors that showed the most significant monthly price increase (0.7%).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and materials sectors intended for subsequent processing did not change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase in energy production and materials for subsequent processing (16.8 per cent) was observed.
In consumer goods production, 6.8 per cent inflation was measured, while for profit-initiating sectors, a 1.4 per cent decrease was measured.
Export sales prices for the industrial sector in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, while they fell by 3.9 per cent over 12 months.
In one month, our national means of payment fell by 1.7 per cent compared to the euro and 7.1 per cent compared to the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it increased by 7.5 per cent compared to the euro and 15.9 per cent compared to the dollar.
