Listen to full volume music for an extended period using portable music devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent damage to the hearing.
This is announced by the European Commission, which, in a communiqué published in Brussels, cites the Scientific Committee's opinion on the unexpected and recently identified health risks (Csseri) of the EU published today.
"of this scientific report - let us read in the note - it appears that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least five years, listen to full volume music using portable musical devices, for more than one hour per day and per week, risk permanent loss of hearing capacity."
"I am concerned that such an important number of young people who frequently use portable music and full-volume mobile phones can unconsciously damage their hearing in an irreparable way," Meglena Kuneva says.
"Scientificly, according to scientific data, the EU is still at a clear risk and we need to react quickly.
What counts most is to raise consumer awareness and make this public information.
We must also review existing control systems in view of scientific opinion so that they are fully effective and can follow new technologies."
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise generated by them.
"Scientifics-conclude the executive EU- confirm that there are good reasons to be concerned, and that the European Commission will now examine with the Member States and other interested parties what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents against exposure to noise from portable music devices and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100Db, but concern increases as to the auditory damage that could result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to limit these data using solutions such as reducing noise levels and duration of exposure.
The Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music devices, who listen to full volume music (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours per week, exceed the current limits on the maximum noise level at the workplace.
Those who listen to music under such conditions during extended periods risk permanent loss of hearing capacity after 5 years.
This affects 5-10% of users of these devices, and their number can be quantified to approximately 2.5 and 10 million people in the U.S.
