The elites are in danger.
The phenomenon had already appeared a few days ago, with the vote of the House of Representatives, contrary to the $700 billion rescue plan approved by the White House: a significant number of Americans were, and still more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the American economy.
And it is the New York Times yesterday that confirms it by communicating that the current crisis divides the Republican Party, even more divided between its early East Coast soul, moderate, favourable to federal institutions as well as to business community, and its new soul, rather conservative, hostile to "the Washingtons" and the world of finance, which is especially powerful in the Central and South states.
The soul, precisely, which became despotic with the vote I was speaking to you at the beginning.
However, what has just been mentioned is just one example of the changes, the major changes that the current economic earthquake has announced or already leaves to run: not only to the United States, but throughout the West, and may not be just here.
In the United States as well as in Europe, the crisis seems to speed up the phenomena that have been occurring for some time, to such an extent that, in the new climate, they are solidified and revealed.
The first of these phenomena is the renewal, the extraordinary revival, of the dual sovereign state category, compared to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions that obviously have close relations with the foreign country, but which, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of individuals and families living in one country, in one state.
This creates an immediate political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of individuals and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically, it is almost only here national.
Political internationalisation seems really out of play, or not much to say: the obvious evidence is provided by the European Union, which, as usual, between the various interests and the various national strategies, does not come to a decision on a common political line.
And so, it is from the government of each state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all a credit condition: when we go through a difficult period, there are only the states that have the economic resources, the mass of financial resources that can try to put things back in place.
They also have the necessary means and legitimacy to use them: two resources of invaluable value, elements that no international market or organization can ever have in a similar manner.
This new emphasis on the state-of-the-nation crisis is, of course, in perfect harmony with the ever greater importance that recent economic developments in the economy tend to attribute to a fairly related factor: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we were now entering the realm of the network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, of non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized at once that our future will need to settle its accounts more and more with things that are not material, such as water, crops, oil.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another from the earth, but which are absolutely linked to a confined space, to a territory.
Thus, who is sovereign, certainly has more maps than the one who is not, that is, the one who has the misfortune to live in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
I now come to the second novelty which, however, foresees a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably said Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who knows how to take over the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leaderships, economic species that have proved inadequate and full of shadows.
And moreover, something even deeper, in a certain sense, even worrying: a discredit, a suffering, an image of inadequacy, a feeling of remoteness that tends to involve the entire class of directors in an increasing number of Western countries.
This further increases the conviction of the various classes, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites until now at their peak, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have the same time, and to be ever more foreign to the opinions of the majority.
In short, The demand for leadership, in an underground way, feeds a powerful and ramified movement of delegitimizations of the ruling classes and traditional political orders, which manifest themselves in the improvised electoral "revolts" or, in the changes of collective moods of the latter recently, from the conservative rise in Austria Bavaria, to the fall of the workers in Britain, to the rebellion of the American congressmen against Bush (and it might well be that the victory of the right in Italy did not come by chance).
It is felt that traditional elites, their parties, their programs, as well as their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their format, someone seems to have ever more difficulty, which does not date today, to understand and therefore to represent the deep layers of Western societies, and that the economic crisis strengthens, increases and potentially shakes in a disproportionate manner.
In view of all this, speaking of a current "rebellion of the masses" on the agenda seems frankly exaggerated.
But we say well, keep your eyes wide open, that's not for no reason.
