Farewell old cinema Paradiso, cities choose historic halls.
Historical cinemas are in favour of the Multiplex.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, it's like a face without eyes"
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, well illustrates what is happening in the large Italian urban centres, but also in the provincial cities,
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth in the periphery of the large halls, and the death of consumption of the mono halls in the central areas of the cities, is one of the major events that we find inevitable and undeniable; it also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear, these are often historical places and loaded with memory, "it's as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a piece of road and so many emotions" observes the director of the New Cinema Paradiso, a film that offered to Tornato 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix de la jure de Cannes, and who narrated the poetry of a provincial hall, and the nostalgia in a way to live the cinema, lost can be forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of traders, mean everything: over the past five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and it is the rooms of the main cities that have paid the most: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, Emilia Romaine is leading with 82 cinemas mono halls lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The evidence that confirms t that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-room cinemas: 195 screens plus in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany as well as Emilia-Romagne.
"The Italian exploitation has developed irrationally" notes Paolo Protti, President of the Annec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it is still necessary to guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a room in a city, these visitors are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplex.
Not to mention the missing deliberation of credit for traders: the previous debt of the state is about EUR 10 million.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, it would take between EUR 16 million and EUR 18 million a year.
Note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, concerned about these closures, decided to resolve the situation through the signing of a protocol between Mayor and Anec, the first of these in Italy, to defend and promote the cinemas mono halls of historical and peripheral centres.
The proposed regulations include tax facilities for managers and benefits to the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area, and special parking rates will be available in some parking lots.
"It is an initiative that pleases" observes Giuseppe Tornatore "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna putting in place other measures.
However, it is clear that, in order to contrast the superpower of multiplexes, traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, as today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Bagheria Supercinema, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Paradise Cinema" which I had already thought for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have experienced so much shared emotions, I turn from the other side not to see the blackboards by the dust.
